<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910412-0164</DOCNO><DOCID>910412-0164.</DOCID><HL>   New York Official Seeks   Health Warning on Carpets</HL><DATE>04/12/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5C</SO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>BUILDING MATERIALS, CONCRETE, GLASS, PAINT (BLD)ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)</IN><RE>NEW YORK (NY)</RE><LP>   NEW YORK -- State Attorney General Robert Abramspetitioned the federal Consumer Product Safety Commission torequire health warnings on new carpeting and installationmaterials, citing potential health hazards.   Mr. Abrams said hundreds of people have complained to thecommission about health problems, including influenza-likesymptoms, rashes, asthma and worsened respiratory conditions,after exposure to new carpet materials. Carpet andinstallation materials may contain as many as 120 chemicals,some of them toxins and carcinogens, he said.</LP><TEXT>   The commission has received 500 complaints about theproblem, including reports of two men dying while installingcarpeting in their boats, Mr. Abrams said. A spokeswoman forMr. Abrams said the cause of death in the two cases isn'tclear.   &quot;Newly installed carpeting may emit dozens of toxic andhazardous chemicals, whether the source is from dyes,synthetic fibers, the adhesives used to install them, thepadding or added treatments,&quot; Mr. Abrams said. The attorneygeneral said he is seeking a comprehensive education programthat would include mandatory warning labels, posters andpamphlets to alert consumers to the potential health hazardsof new carpeting.   The spokeswoman said doctors have suggested a two-week tofour-week period of keeping windows open after new carpetingis installed.</TEXT></DOC>